Discussion: 

(quick summary of pattern)
- aim of the present study was to investigate etc... 
- by means of simultaneous opposite adaptation
- not only explore whether other voice cues interfere, but whether they modulate emotion adaptation in a sense that allows efficient tracking of relevant emotional changes from multiple sources simultaneously. 
- Accordingly, predicted the effects for stable speaker cues such as gender and identity, but not for pseudoword. 
- Indeed, there was a clear pattern for gender. And for pseudoword as well. For speaker identity, it was conflicting
- in what follows, patterns are discussed in more detail, then limitations, then outlook for future reseach

Recalibrating to stable speaker cues: 

- clear pattern for voice gender
- replication of the study of Bestelmeyer, but in the auditory domain, where it was never shown befpre
- it was showsn before that gender interferes with emotion, but rather in terms of bias in certain emotional direction
- this here is not a universal bias (i.e. female always fearful), but a context specific modulation in either direction

- speaker identitiy, a completely different pictre: way more conflicting
- it only worked for one female speaker, 
- Why was the pattern so clear for speaker gender, and so conflicting for speaker identity? Why not a decisive answer, both theoretical and methodological consideration offer potential explanations 

Theoretical: 

- voice space theory (speakers are stored somewhere in a multidimensional voice space and represented by their deviation from each other a central midpoint, providing the global reference)
- although its a model for representation of identity, not dynamic information such as emotion. Nevertheless, it provides useful for an understanding of the current data. 
- there have been arguments for distinct voice spaces for male and female voices, with two different references
- male and female voices are per se processed in relation to differenc reference frames, linked to different neural networks
- build-in neural architecture for separate tracking of male and female voices
- also allowing for separate recalibration to emotions (Nussbaum 2022) -> fits the reduction in emotion adaptation across gender
- different speaker identities of the same speaker gender are processed in relation to the same reference frame, employing similar neural-circuits
- which aggrevates separate recalibration to emotions
- could explain why the effect is maybe much smaller, but does not have to absent completely (as it was also shown in the present data)


Methodological 

- acoustically difference between male and female voices: male version of anger and fear and female version of it

- for simultaneous opposite aftereffects to work, there needs to be no classification ambiguity to voice dimensions
- no problem of perception of gender (add a little info about timing etc) -> readily and easily, in unfamiliar speakers

- for unfamiliar identities, this is less clear: perception of unfamiliar identities is invariant/prone to intraindividual variability introduced by the pseudowords and emotions
- short utterances, and the only familiarization happened during the baseline task
- thus, fear and angry voices by the same speaker could have been interpreted as different speaker identities, and then simulatenous opposite adaptation cant work

- in familiar speakers, the story is entirely differen (Pinheiro): more stable, variability incorporated into the representation
- and familiar with very idiosyncratic style of emotional expression
- therefore: this should definitely be replicated with familiar voices
 
- speaker identity which does not provide convincing evidence, but a promising starting point for future research

Dynamic linguistic cues: 

- no effect
- note for pseudowords we did not only see an absence of effects, but actual strong evidence for the null-hypothesis
- does not mean that words dont carry emotional meaning: when they have semantics, they do and that does interfere with emotional prosody
- does also not mean that all linguistic features are equally well-suited to express emotions
- there was an effect of pseudoword: /belam/, the only one starting with a plosive, was perceived as more angry, because plosive are effective to express emotional arousal such as in anger
(check: link of swaring words and phonemes) Lev-Aris Papers, Aryani et al. (2018)
- what the current data show is that for recalibration to the current emotional context, this linguistic information is averaged out.


Limitations and outlook: 

- strength of the study lies in the same stimuli for all experiments
- study was powered after the vorbild of Bestelmeyer, but for speaker identity, is may be much smaller, and thus not enough for speaker identiy
- problematic confounds between identities and emotional intensity (and to a lesser degree for pseudowords as well)
- while that should not have been a KO-kriterium for simulaneous opposite adaptaion -> is results into main effects
- it could have reduced statistical power substantially, and that in a paradigm where the effect was maybe smaller, render it non-detectable

- increase linguistic variability: approximants for example
- and yeah... personally familiar speakers


